{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17529404","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17529404"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:55:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:55:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14387"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14387","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14387"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.37,0.24,0.12,0.08,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7082"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87420"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7082","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7082"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14387"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71639"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"107"},{"type":"tags","id":"1336"},{"type":"tags","id":"4298"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16895"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16973"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30043"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48260"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87420","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/87420"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 18-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of worsening pain and redness on his left shin following a dog bite. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He does not smoke.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 78/min, blood pressure 120/88 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There is a 3 cm area of erythema, swelling, and necrosis on his left anterior shin with evidence of a recent dog bite. The surrounding skin is warm to touch and tender on palpation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following bacteria is most likely to be associated with this patient\u0027s soft tissue infection?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pasteurella species","Staphylococcus aureus","Eikenella corrodens","Streptococcus species","Capnocytophaga canimorsus"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPasteurella species\u003C/strong\u003E, particularly \u003Cem\u003EPasteurella multocida\u003C/em\u003E, are the most likely bacteria associated with this patient\u0027s soft tissue infection. These gram-negative bacteria are part of the normal oral flora of dogs and are frequently isolated from dog bite wounds, often as the predominant pathogen. They typically cause rapidly progressing cellulitis within 24-48 hours after the bite.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003EStreptococcus species\u003C/strong\u003E are common skin flora that can be introduced into the wound during a bite. While not specific to dog bites, these bacteria are often involved in the polymicrobial nature of bite wound infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEikenella corrodens\u003C/strong\u003E is more commonly found in human bite wounds rather than dog bites. It is part of the normal human oral flora and is rarely isolated from dog bite infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECapnocytophaga canimorsus\u003C/strong\u003E is a gram-negative bacterium found in the oral flora of dogs and cats. It can cause severe infections, especially in immunocompromised individuals or those with asplenia. While it is associated with dog bites, it is less commonly isolated than Pasteurella species.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of dog bite infections typically involves wound cleaning, debridement if necessary, and empiric antibiotic therapy. Amoxicillin with clavulanic acid is an appropriate empiric antibiotic choice for dog bite infections as it covers most of these common pathogens.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Common bacteria in dog bite infections include Pasteurella species, Staphylococcus aureus, Streptococcus species, and Capnocytophaga canimorsus.","Eikenella corrodens is more commonly associated with human bites rather than dog bites.","Empiric antibiotic therapy for dog bites should cover common pathogens found in the canine oral flora."],"references":["Bite wound infections, including clenched-fist injury infections. In: Therapeutic guidelines. May 2022. Available at: https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/","Abrahamian FM, Goldstein EJ. Microbiology of animal bite wound infections. Clin Microbiol Rev. 2011 Apr;24(2):231-46. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3122494/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71639"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14387"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71639","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/71639"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-27T21:37:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-27T21:38:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7082"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87420"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"